Use this option to assign multiple MSNs to the available B channels so that incoming calls can be logged more accurately. This setting allows incoming faxes to be routed to individual users by assigning them different MSNs and is recommended for operation with the MS Small Business Server (SBS)/ BackOffice Server 2000 (BOS).

Use this option to provide your TAPI applications with one TAPI line for each B channel available. This setting is recommended for operation with programs like the Windows Phone Dialer and MS Outlook.

This function allows fax documents to be accepted even from remote sites that signal incorrectly. When this option is active, TAPI Services for CAPI also accept calls that the remote site explicitly signaled as "voice calls".
Note: This feature can cause malfunctions when it is set for a line that is configured normally (TAPI Services for CAPI accept all calls).

On some PBXs the service indicator for TAPI Services for CAPI must be changed. The setting "Analog fax" is generally correct. When this setting is active, TAPI Services for CAPI signals the remote site from the analog network like a fax machine (using the Audio/Voice service indicator) and thus can connect to all fax sites. Unfortunately, many PBXs do not understand "ISDN Fax", the setting that would be correct in an ISDN network and thus may require this setting to send faxes.
